title: A Survey: Collaborative Hardware and Software Design in the Era of Large Language Models
summary:
The rapid development of large language models (LLMs) has significantly
transformed the field of artificial intelligence, demonstrating remarkable
capabilities in natural language processing and moving towards multi-modal
functionality. These models are increasingly integrated into diverse
applications, impacting both research and industry. However, their development
and deployment present substantial challenges, including the need for extensive
computational resources, high energy consumption, and complex software
optimizations. Unlike traditional deep learning systems, LLMs require unique
optimization strategies for training and inference, focusing on system-level
efficiency. This paper surveys hardware and software co-design approaches
specifically tailored to address the unique characteristics and constraints of
large language models. This survey analyzes the challenges and impacts of LLMs
on hardware and algorithm research, exploring algorithm optimization, hardware
design, and system-level innovations. It aims to provide a comprehensive
understanding of the trade-offs and considerations in LLM-centric computing
systems, guiding future advancements in AI. Finally, we summarize the existing
efforts in this space and outline future directions toward realizing
production-grade co-design methodologies for the next generation of large
language models and AI systems.
